Define our control system as the precise fraction of gas $n_2$ that remains trapped inside the chamber at the end of the timeline. This sub-gas expands reversibly and adiabatically against the escaping gas to eventually fill the fixed structural volume $V$. Its local pressure transitions from $P_1$ down to atmospheric equilibrium $P_0$.
  
  Its temperature change satisfies the relation: $T_2 = T_1 (P_0 / P_1)^(1 - 1/gamma)$.
  
  Applying the ideal gas law to the static vessel volume $V$:
  - Initially: $V = (n_1 R T_1) / P_1$
  - Final state: $V = (n_2 R T_2) / P_0$
  
  Equating both expressions for volume:
  $ n_2 / n_1 = P_0 / P_1 dot T_1 / T_2 $
  Substituting the adiabatic temperature ratio $T_1 / T_2 = (P_1 / P_0)^(1 - 1/gamma}$:
  $ n_2 / n_1 = P_0 / P_1 dot (P_1 / P_0)^(1 - 1/gamma) = P_0^(1/gamma) / P_1^(1/gamma) = (P_0 / P_1)^(1/gamma) => n_2 = n_1 (P_0 / P_1)^(1/gamma) $